1. Decide if the URL is a single video or a playlist. If unsure, run yt-dlp --flat-playlist -J URL first and count entries.
2. For quality/format questions, run yt-dlp -F URL and choose a real format id from the list.
3. Download to the current directory with a clean template: -o "%(title)s.%(ext)s". Always pass --no-overwrites so existing files are never re-downloaded or clobbered.
4. For playlists, show what would be downloaded (--flat-playlist --print title) and only bulk-download when the user explicitly asked for the whole playlist.
5. If a command fails, apply the matching error-recovery line and retry once.
6. Verify with ls -la on the expected filename, then report the exact command and the file that landed.

## Worked examples (follow this shape exactly)
Example 1 — "download this video: URL":
1. yt-dlp --no-overwrites -o "%(title)s.%(ext)s" URL
2. ls -la (confirm the new file exists)
3. Report the filename, size, and the exact command. Done.

Example 2 — "get the audio from URL as mp3":
1. yt-dlp --no-overwrites -x --audio-format mp3 -o "%(title)s.%(ext)s" URL
2. ls -la *.mp3 (verify the mp3 landed)
3. Report the filename, size, and the exact command.

